{{Taxobox | color = lightgrey | name = '''''Candidatus'' Atelocyanobacterium thalassa''' | regnum = [[Bacterium|Bacteria]] | phylum = [[Cyanobacteria]] | ordo = [[Chroococcales]] | species = '''''Ca.'' Atelocyanobacterium thalassa''' | genus_authority = <center>Thompson et al., 2012</center> }}
'''''[[Candidatus]]'' Atelocyanobacterium thalassa''' (previously '''cyanobacterium UCYN-A,''') is a [[species]] of [[cyanobacteria]] commonly found throughout the world's oceans.<ref name=DOI10.1126science.1222700>{{cite journal|last1=Thompson|first1=A. W.|last2=Foster|first2=R. A.|last3=Krupke|first3=A.|last4=Carter|first4=B. J.|last5=Musat|first5=N.|last6=Vaulot|first6=D.|last7=Kuypers|first7=M. M. M.|last8=Zehr|first8=J. P.|title=Unicellular Cyanobacterium Symbiotic with a Single-Celled Eukaryotic Alga|journal=Science|date=20 September 2012|volume=337|issue=6101|pages=1546–1550|doi=10.1126/science.1222700|pmid=22997339}}</ref> Unlike many other cyanobacteria, ''A. thalassa'' lacks the ability to perform [[photosynthesis]]. Instead, it is found in a [[symbiosis|symbiotic]] relationship with photosynthetic [[algae]]. ''A. thalassa'' [[nitrogen fixation|fixes nitrogen]] for the algae, while the algae provides carbon for ''A. thalassa'' through photosynthesis.<ref name=UCSC>{{cite web|url=http://news.ucsc.edu/2012/09/symbiosis.html |accessdate=13 January 2017 |title=Unusual symbiosis discovered in marine microorganisms |publisher=University of California Santa Cruz Newscenter |date=20 September 2012 |author=Tim Stephens}}</ref>
==History== ''A. thalassa'' was first described in 1998 as a nitrogen-fixing bacteria with a much-reduced genome.<ref name=UCSC/> The microbe was originally given the name UCYN-A for "unicellular cyanobacteria group A".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jzehrlab.com/ucyn-a |title=Zehr Laboratory |accessdate=13 January 2017 |publisher=University of California, Santa Cruz}}</ref> In 2012, ''A. thalassa'' was described to be in a symbiotic association with the unicellular algae ''[[Braarudosphaera bigelowii]]'' and ''[[Chrysochromulina parkeae]]''.<ref name=DOI10.1126science.1222700/>
==Biochemistry== ''A. thalassa'' lacks a variety of metabolic components common to cyanobacteria, including the oxygen-producing [[photosystem II]] complex of the [[photosynthesis|photosynthetic apparatus]], the [[carboxysome]], enzymes of the [[Calvin cycle|Calvin]] and [[tricarboxylic acid cycle|tricarboxylic acid]] cycles, as well as several enzymes involved in [[amino acid]] synthesis.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature08786 |author1=Tripp, H. James |author2=Bench, Shellie R. |author3=Turk, Kendra A. |author4=Foster, Rachel A. |author5=Desany, Brian A. |author6=Niazi, Faheem |author7=Affourtit, Jason P. |author8=Zehr, Jonathan P. |year=2009 |title=Metabolic streamlining in an open-ocean nitrogen-fixing cyanobacterium |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |issue= 7285|pages=90–94 |volume=464 |pmid=20173737}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Bothe, H. |author2=Tripp, H. J. |author3=Zehr, J. P. |year=2010 |title=Unicellular cyanobacteria with a new mode of life: the lack of photosynthetic oxygen evolution allows nitrogen fixation to proceed |journal=[[Arch Microbiol]] |issue=192 |pages=783–90}}</ref>
