'''Tuberous receptors''' are [[electroreceptor]]s that are specialized to respond to high-frequency electrical fields ([[Electric organ (biology)|electric organ discharge]]s or EODs), and hence are found only in [[fish]] with an active electrical sense that can generate their own electrical fields.  They are mostly found on weakly electric fishes such as [[gymnotiform]]s and [[mormyrid]]s. These receptors are particularly receptive to their own electrical fields, and can detect perturbations caused by foreign objects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Physiology of Tuberous Electrosensory Systems|url=http://www.web.pdx.edu/~zelickr/sensory-physiology/articles/2012-articles/wk10-electro-magneto-noci/electroreception/kawasaki-physiology-tuberous-systems.pdf|first1=Masashi|last1=Kawasaki}}</ref>

There are two types of tuberous receptors, t-type and p-type.

Species which use tuberous receptors include the [[Gymnotiformes|glass knife fish]] (''Eigenmannia virescens''), a gymnotiform.
